Mount Rushmore is a famous monument located in the Black Hills of South Dakota, featuring the faces of four U.S. presidents carved into the side of a mountain. The four presidents whose faces are carved on Mount Rushmore are George Washington, Thomas Jefferson, Theodore Roosevelt, and Abraham Lincoln.
The carving was designed by sculptor Gutzon Borglum and took 14 years to complete, from 1927 to 1941. The faces are carved into the granite of the mountain and are over 60 feet tall. The carving was originally intended to include other figures and scenes, but the project was scaled back due to funding issues and the death of Borglum.
The carving was completed in 1941, and it has since become one of the most iconic landmarks in the United States, attracting millions of visitors each year. The carving is a symbol of American history and democracy, and it is often seen as a representation of the principles and values that the United States was founded upon.
